{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}} {{Coord|40.792820|-73.919188|scale:2500|display=title}} {{Infobox institute |name = John McEnroe Tennis Academy |image = |image_size = |image_alt = |caption = |latin_name = |motto = |founder = [[John McEnroe]] |established = 2010 |mission = |focus = |president = |chairman = |head_label = |head = |faculty = |adjunct_faculty = |staff = |key_people = |budget = |endowment = |debt = |num_members = |subsidiaries = |owner = |non-profit_slogan = |former_name = |location = [[Randall's Island]] |city = New York City |state = New York |province = |country = |coor = |address = One Randall's Island, New York, NY 10035 |website = [http://www.johnmcenroetennisacademy.com/ johnmcenroetennisacademy.com] |dissolved = |footnotes = }} The '''John McEnroe Tennis Academy''' (JMTA) is a [[tennis]] academy founded by tennis Hall of Famer [[John McEnroe]] in [[New York City]].<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/tennis/news/story?id=5521560|title=John McEnroe starts tennis academy in Randall's Island |work=ESPN|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name="nyt two"/><ref name="TIME">{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2014403,00.html|title=Can John McEnroe's Tennis Academy Lift U.S. Talent?|date=August 30, 2010|work=TIME|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name="New York Magazine">{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/sports/67633/|title=How John McEnroe Plans to Save Tennis by Opening a Tennis Academy on Randall's Island |work=New York Magazine|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennisnow.com/News/Featured-News/John-McEnroe-Tennis-Academy-Launches-On-NYC-s-Rand.aspx|title=John McEnroe Tennis Academy Launches On NYC's Randall's Island |publisher=Tennis Now|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref> The Academy was founded in September 2010, on a 20-court (10 deco turf, 10 clay courts) $18 million tennis complex, designed by [[Ricardo Zurita]], on [[Randalls Island]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref name="ESPN"/><ref name="TIME"/><ref name="New York Magazine"/><ref name="nyt one"/><ref name="Archtober">{{cite news|author1=Julia Cohen|title=Building of the Day #5|url=http://www.archtober.org/botd-sportime-tennis-academy/|work=Archtober|date=Oct 14, 2014}}</ref> McEnroe launched the Academy in collaboration with Claude Okin, managing partner of Sportime New York.<ref name="nyt one">{{cite news|author1=Harvey Araton|title=Building the Next McEnroe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/08/sports/tennis/08tennis.html|work=The New York Times|date=May 7, 2010}}</ref>
[[File:Rubin US16 (53) (29235540794).jpg|thumb| right |170px |[[Noah Rubin (tennis)|Noah Rubin]]]] McEnroe's teaching philosophy emphasizes short intense periods of tennis training balanced by plenty of time pursuing other sports and activities.<ref name="nyt two">{{cite news|author1=Harvey Araton|title=12-Year-Old Girl May Embody McEnroe's Vision|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/08/sports/tennis/08mcenroe.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name="nyt one"/>
Alumni include [[Noah Rubin (tennis)|Noah Rubin]], who won the Boys' Singles tournament at [[2014 Wimbledon Championships – Boys' Singles|Wimbledon]] in July 2014, and the 2014 [[Boy's Junior National Tennis Championship|U.S. Tennis Association's Boys 18s National Championships]] in both singles and doubles the following month, is a product of the Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysportsday.com/2014/08/10/john-mcenroe-tennis-academy-student-noah-rubin-completes-sweep-of-singles-doubles-in-kalamazoo-earns-us-open-wild-cards/|title=John McEnroe Tennis Academy Student Noah Rubin Completes Sweep Of Singles, Doubles In Kalamazoo, Earns US Open Wild Cards|publisher=NY Sports Day|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Eric Koningsberg|title=Can U.S. Men's Tennis Rise Again?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/24/magazine/can-us-mens-tennis-rise-again.html|work=The New York Times|date=Aug 22, 2014}}</ref> In September 2014, Rubin was ranked the No. 1 [[Division I (NCAA)|Division 1]] college freshman by the [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association]] (ITA) while playing for [[Wake Forest University]], and sophomore [[Jamie Loeb]] – another product of the Academy – was named the No. 1 Division 1 female college player while playing for [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportimeny.com/blog/|title=jmta|publisher=|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itatennis.com/AwardsAndRankings/Rankings/2014-15_ITA_NCAA_Division_I_Men_s_Rankings/2014_Division_I_Preseason_Men_s_Newcomer_Freshman_Rankings.htm|title=2014 Division I Preseason Men's Newcomer/Freshman Rankings|publisher=|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itatennis.com/AwardsAndRankings/Rankings/2014-15_ITA_NCAA_Division_I_Women_s_Rankings/2014_Division_I_Preseason_Women_s_Singles_Rankings.htm|title=2014 Division I Preseason Women's Singles Rankings|publisher=|accessdate=October 1, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006065751/http://www.itatennis.com/AwardsAndRankings/Rankings/2014-15_ITA_NCAA_Division_I_Women_s_Rankings/2014_Division_I_Preseason_Women_s_Singles_Rankings.htm|archivedate=October 6, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
