[[File:Inov8 Evoskin Minimalist Shoes.jpg|thumb|Evoskins - a type of minimalist shoe]] '''Minimalist shoes''' are shoes intended to closely approximate [[barefoot running]] or walking conditions in comparison to traditional shoes.<ref>{{cite web|title=My Shoes Are Killing Me!?|url=https://www.lisbethjoe.com/single-post/2017/10/01/My-Shoes-Are-Killing-Me-Repost-from-Freakonomics|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What are Minimalist Running Shoes?|url=http://www.runblogger.com/2011/09/what-are-minimalist-running-shoes.html|accessdate=8 August 2013}}</ref> They have reduced cushioning, thin soles, and are of lighter weight than other running shoes, allowing for more sensory contact for the foot on the ground while simultaneously providing the feet with some protection from ground hazards and conditions (such as pebbles and dirt).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.runnersworld.com/running-shoes-gear/barefoot-running|title=Barefoot Running|work=Runner's World}}</ref> Research shows that wearing a minimalist shoe can help improve foot strength and arch function.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Elizabeth E.|last2=Whitcome|first2=Katherine K.|last3=Lieberman|first3=Daniel E.|last4=Norton|first4=Heather L.|last5=Dyer|first5=Rachael E.|date=2014-06-01|title=The effect of minimal shoes on arch structure and intrinsic foot muscle strength|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2095254614000374|journal=Journal of Sport and Health Science|series=Special Issue on “Barefoot and Minimal Shoe Running”|volume=3|issue=2|pages=74–85|doi=10.1016/j.jshs.2014.03.011}}</ref>
== Types == Generally, there are two types of minimalist shoes:<ref>{{cite web|title=Barefoot/Minimalist Running Shoes: How to Choose|url=http://www.rei.com/learn/expert-advice/how-to-choose-barefoot-minimalist-running-shoes.html|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> * ''Barefoot Running Shoes'' are characterized by their zero drop from heel to toe, no arch support, minimal cushioning at the heel, and a very thin sole of around 3-10mm. Also, the toe box is considerably wider to provide more space to the toes, whereby they slightly resemble the shape of ducks feet, when viewed from above and compared to traditional shoes. Few product lines fall into this category. Examples include the [[Vibram FiveFingers]] and [[Merrell_(company)|Merrell]] Glove, which use an outsole produced by [[Vibram]], or the [[Xero_Shoes|Xero]] Prio. * ''Minimalist Running Shoes'' are in-between traditional running shoes and barefoot running shoes. They have a reduced heel-to-toe drop of about 4–8&nbsp;mm, reduced cushioning and reduced or no arch support. The toe box is usually in-between barefoot and traditional running shoes.
In recognition of the barefoot running movement, major companies also started producing shoes targeted at this customer segment. However, these shoes do not usually meet the requirement of a minimal or barefoot shoe. Examples include: * The [[Nike Free]], which has a 17&nbsp;mm heel and is marketed as minimalist running shoe, though this designation is disputed by some.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hutchinson |first=Alex |url=http://www.runnersworld.com/running-shoes/do-minimalist-shoes-really-simulate-barefoot-running |title=Do Minimalist Shoes Really Simulate Barefoot Running? &#124; Runner's World |publisher=Runnersworld.com |date=2013-01-12 |accessdate=2013-08-16}}</ref> * The Adidas Adizero line, which has a heel-to-toe drop of 4 to 10mm, a total heel height of up to 30mm and a comparatively traditional, narrow toe box. * The [[Champion_(sportswear)|Champion]] Alpha. In contrast to ''barefoot'' and ''minimal'' shoes, one of the marketing terms repeatedly employed for this product segment is ''natural running''.
== See also == *[[Vibram FiveFingers]] *[[Vivobarefoot]] *[[Xero Shoes]]
